## Postgres service\
\
```yaml\
  postgres:\
```\
- This defines a service named `postgres`. Docker Compose will create and manage a container for it.\
\
```yaml\
    image: postgres:16\
```\
- Use the official PostgreSQL image, version 16, from Docker Hub.\
- That image includes the Postgres server and default tools.\
\
```yaml\
    container_name: nexus-postgres\
```\
- The actual container will have the name `nexus-postgres` instead of a random auto-generated name.\
- Useful when running commands like `docker logs nexus-postgres` or `docker exec -it nexus-postgres bash`.\
\
```yaml\
    restart: unless-stopped\
```\
- Docker will automatically restart this container if it exits/crashes, unless *you* explicitly stop it.\
- Good for keeping your database always running during development.\
\
### Postgres environment variables\
\
```yaml\
    environment:\
      POSTGRES_USER: nexus_user\
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: nexus_password\
      POSTGRES_DB: nexus_db\
```\
These are **crucial**; they tell Postgres how to initialize the database:\
\
- `POSTGRES_USER: nexus_user`\
  - On first startup, Postgres will create a database user/role named `nexus_user`.\
  - This is your **Postgres username** in this setup.\
\
- `POSTGRES_PASSWORD: nexus_password`\
  - Sets the password for the `nexus_user` role.\
  - Clients must supply this password when connecting (unless using trust or other auth methods, but by default, yes).\
\
- `POSTGRES_DB: nexus_db`\
  - On first startup, Postgres will create a database with the name `nexus_db`.\
  - That database will be owned by `nexus_user`.\
\
So:  \
**Username:** `nexus_user`  \
**Password:** `nexus_password`  \
**Default DB:** `nexus_db`\
